Firstly, date-time values when stored in text should be in standard [ISO 8601][1] format. For a date-only value, that would be YYYY-MM-DD. 

As for your `Date` class, dont invent one. Use the class given to you, `java.time.LocalDate`. 

Since you have non-standard inputs, define a pair of `DateTimeFormatter` objects to match each of the formats you expect. 

    DateTimeFormatter longer = DateTimeFormatter.ofPattern( &quot;MM/dd/uuuu&quot; ) ;
    DateTimeFormatter shorter =  ;

For each input, attempt to parse. 

    LocalDate ld = LocalDate.parse( input , longer ) ;

When making that attempt, use a try-catch to trap for `DateTimeParseException`. 

Repeat for the shorter formatter. If both throw the exception, you have unexpected faulty input. 

Before parsing, test for a `null` with `Objects.requireNonNull`. That method throws an exception if null. 

And you can test to see if your input is either empty (no characters) or if all the characters are whitespace. 

    if ( input.isBlank() ) {  }


  [1]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601

