There a lot of ways to do it, the simplest is using built in class of Spring `CommonsRequestLoggingFilter`
```
@Configuration
public class RequestLoggingFilterConfig {

    @Bean
    public CommonsRequestLoggingFilter logFilter() {
        CommonsRequestLoggingFilter filter
          = new CommonsRequestLoggingFilter();
        filter.setIncludeQueryString(true);
        filter.setIncludePayload(true);
        filter.setMaxPayloadLength(10000);
        filter.setIncludeHeaders(false);
        filter.setAfterMessagePrefix(&quot;REQUEST DATA: &quot;);
        return filter;
    }
}
```
Then turn on debug level log in `application.properties` file
```
logging.level.org.springframework.web.filter.CommonsRequestLoggingFilter=DEBUG
```
For more information, pls refer to this [doc](https://www.baeldung.com/spring-http-logging)

C `const char *` maps to Java `String`.  JNA has mappings for `size_t` depending on your operating system.

You generally don&#39;t need, and should not add the `ByReference` tags. These add another level of pointer indirection which is usually wrong.  Inline in structures you don&#39;t want the pointer, and JNA defaults to ByValue.  As function/method arguments you usually do want the pointer, and JNA defaults to ByReference here.

You do have an array of Strings in your Structure, but JNA requires the array length to be declared when initialized. This works if you&#39;re declaring it on the Java side but requires some extra steps to override `read()` on the structure if reading it from the native side.

You can just delete your `FfiStr` structure and use `String` for that mapping.  You could wrap it inside a Structure (for type safety, for example), but do so without using `ByReference` on it since the `String` mapping already includes the pointer. 

For your second structure, it&#39;s a bit more complicated.  When declaring a Structure, JNA allocates the memory for it, so it needs to know the size of the array.  So you need to give data a nonzero initialization and then overwrite the value and re-allocate memory in the constructor.

In addition, the memory allocated for a Structure must be contiguous native memory. Declaring an array in Java with primitives allocates native memory, but for Strings and other Objects it doesn&#39;t.  Nested structure arrays can be created with contiguous memory with `toArray()` (if you chose to map `FfiStr` as a structure).

You can always just map the String array argument to a `Pointer` since that&#39;s actually what&#39;s happening on the native side; but that also requires you to handle allocating the memory and writing the string array yourself.

For String Arrays, JNA provides a [`StringArray`][1] class which handles all the contiguous memory allocation.  Note there are multiple constructors to allow for Windows (UTF-16 wide strings) vs. *nix-based implementations. Use the appropriate one for your OS (or provide both if you&#39;re cross-platform).

While `StringArray` handles the contiguous allocation, you need to map its `Pointer` superclass inside the `Structure`.

Some other notes:
 - you haven&#39;t indicated how you have mapped `Size_t` but it is generally pointer-sized.  If you&#39;re on a 64-bit operating system it&#39;s going to be 8 bytes.  JNA has `size_t` mappings you can use.
 - The method `create_schema` argument `FfiList_FfiStr attr_names` does not include the `*` indicating a by-reference value, indicating the structure should be passed on the stack by value.  So you need to add a `ByValue` tag to your structure and use it in the method call.

```java
@FieldOrder ({&quot;count&quot;, &quot;data&quot;})
public class FfiList_FfiStr extends Structure{

    public class ByValue extends FfiList_FfiStr implements Structure.ByValue {};

    public size_t count; // use JNA&#39;s size_t
    public Pointer data;

    public FfiList_FfiStr(String[] attr){
        count = new Size_t(attr.length);
        data = new StringArray(attr);
    }
}
```
and
```java
int create_schema(
   String schema_name,
   String schema_version,
   String issuer_id,
   FfiList_FfiStr.ByValue attr_names,
   size_t.ByReference result_p 
);
```

  [1]: http://java-native-access.github.io/jna/5.13.0/javadoc/com/sun/jna/StringArray.html

