#### Problem
With your actual structure, java can&#39;t ensure that `min` will always be initialized

#### Solution

You need to some `else if` and `else` to prove java that `min` will be defined

    public static int GetMin(int a, int b) {
        int min;
        int max;
        if (a == b) {
            return a;
        } else if (a &gt; b) {
            min = b;
            max = a;
        } else {
            min = a;
            max = b;
        }
        return min;
    }

As when `a==b` and when `a&lt;b` you return `a`, you could initialize `min` with `a`

    public static int GetMin(int a, int b) {
        int min = a;
        if (a &gt; b) {
            min = b;
        } 
        return min;
    }

Or use ternary operator

    public static int GetMin(int a, int b) {
        return a &gt; b ? b : a;
    }

upd: in discussion we resolved that the reason is in Java Language Specification (https://docs.oracle.com/javase/specs/jls/se8/jls8.pdf), not in `javac`. 

***Overall as a solution you can initialize `min`, `max` variables or use `if-then-else` expression***

I think that it is bug of compiler, because in any case of this execution we will get minimum value. As a solution you can write so:

    public static int GetMin(int a, int b) {
        int min;
        int max;
        if (a == b) {
            return a;
        } else if (a &gt; b) {
            min = b;
            max = a;
        } else {
            min = a;
            max = b;
        }
        return min;
    }

Or simply use:

    public static int GetMin(int a, int b) {
        return a &gt; b ? b : a;
    }

